It's too technical for a layman to understand and practice quizzes are tough, hence leaving this course in between. Please take some clue from google project management course on how to make learning interesting and easy.
I have applied for financial aid, please check the same.
not able to submit assignments.
The Coursera UX coupled with the instructor's tendency to wander and the fact that the course didn't have a clear learning trajectory for each section made it incredibly difficult to follow.
Sadly the course material was not presented in a vivid and practical way. Furthermore the test question were quite different from the materials in the course.
Very poor quality, it´s really annoying this thing of writing on a screen all the time .

I'm sorry but I found the course really confused and confusing. There's no solid structure in explaining the topics, no method. No schema. Nothing. It's a mix of info. it's supposed to be an intermediate course, but you should have so many pre-requirements to understand topics and contents.
A very very complex failed course, I rate 0 out of 10
frustration course, too much empty thoughts and little specificity. It was very difficult to listen and assimilate the information at the speed with which the teacher read it. Wasted time
VEDIO LECTURING NOT UNDERSTANDING...POWER POINT PRESENTATION NEEDED, I NEVER RECONMENDED THIS COURSE
it was mentioned that the course is for free but later after completion they are asking for money for certificate
I don't recommend it. The material is not useful and the course is very impractical. Acceptable content but a very low time investment/learning ratio.

I don't mind his [Alex's] personal views; I do mind his baseless, just-said-like-that opinions.
I don't mind his [Alex's] satirical comments; I do mind his constant mention of Resources section (I am not to be toggled between Videos and Resources AT ALL TIMES; it is to be a supplement and not a complement here!) P.S. I was an aspiring Product Manager, but (sadly) now I am not. And so, Thank You for that!

Too much text, to much theory and lots of tools. Felt difficulty in following the course. Need to be so cautious. Exhaustive with too many videos and questions in the last. The Digital Transformation and Design thinking was awesome and i was able to follow. Customer centric and Digital product mgmt is very heavy to learn and follow and keep track on the concepts.  Just pushing myself hard to understand since i paid for this course. But i was happy with Digital transformation and Design thinking.
its very hard to take noted
communication is too complex. Need to put the point across in simple sentences with simple easy-to-understand examples

One of the worst Instructor's at all of my life, he can't focus and give the information easily, and he keeps using his pen drawing on the Screen. What's the benefit of the slides if he doesn't use the information on it probably. he display something and talking about something else!
realmente solo es teoría y herramientas aplicadas a producto, pero no hay casos prácticos ni contenido aplicable, probaré los demás cursos, seguro la especialización es mas completa

The lecturer is a bit of a scatter brain with concepts, going back and forth with concepts. I would rather clear dot-points on the power-points that explain the concepts in typed text words rather than long verbal descriptions with messy scribbling over slides that constantly come on and off the screen (just have the slide, actual key concepts written and then we can listen to you waffle on, i don't need to see you talking - I need to see the slide!). The concepts are not at all difficult but when given in a disjointed manner and having to constantly refer to other topics is very annoying when they could have been presented in a more logical manner. I get the feeling the lecturer is more interested in himself talking and playing teacher (like my niece who likes to talk to her teddies and scribble on a whiteboard) than teaching the content.
The course is not right to the point! Is needed to be more focused.

The slides were not informative enough, and the fact that the professor was constantly circling and underlining things on them was distracting and dirty. In addition, I found the division of videos into such small increments and dividing videos into parts was unnecessary.
I'm not satisfied with this course. The content is interesting but explained in a very unprofessional way.
Not exhaustive

I understand that this is a multiple choice type assessment course, however many of the questions were created based on the professor's definitions, and quite often they used trickery around what is very grey lines between the choices. I felt in many cases many of the answers were highly subjective and could depend on multiple variables, that were left out. A better course would be like the Gamification one I did, wherein I explained my rationale given scenarios. I feel overall this would be a more reinforcing method of learning these theories.

I believe the instructor has a very good practical knowledge but in comparison with the google's courses that I've passed, it is very  unorganized.in the middle of the weeks you don't know the point of  things you are learning. even in videos introduction mostly the problem to be tackled is not very clear.
A lot of information was covered. My biggest critique is to structure the quizzes in ways that more directly align with the information taught.
F​ound this course more on the strategic front.
Information is crammed up
​not very beginner friendly

A useful introductory course. There is scope for improving quality of examples, test questions and more importantly interviews ( there is big difference compared to the insights derived from the interviews in Digital Transformation Module by BCG)
Decent overview.

I am a PM with 5 years of solid experience. Did I learn something new? Of course! But, felt the instructor rushes through the course and keep things at very high level. Overall the course is kind of okay.

Course content was good, yet the quizzes and length of videos were overkill.  For example, the first 2 questions on the Week 4 final were in relation to a concept relating to market types from the first week.  There were 2 answers that buried a trick response and would have failed someone that selected them.  These questions would be okay, if they had tremendous relevancy to the actual course, yet they do not.  I passed the first time, yet these types of questions are not helpful for someone trying to learn and stay engaged in a course like this.  The tools and functional concepts are of greater value for a course like this.  Also, the course felt drawn out with way too much filler.  Even at 2X, the course seems to drag a bit.  I am highly interested in the content, yet have difficulty staying connected with the pace and trick quizzes thrown throughout the course.  Hopefully the feedback will help make some adjustments.  Even if the quizzes were designed more appropriately, I'd probably give this a 5 and I'm sure there'd be more engagement by other learners.
Need practical exmaples , its all theory
The structure is not so helpful, the moderator is with the examples not helpful, this course take a lot energy.
Thank you sir , for making this course really interesting .

I learned a couple of helpful frameworks. Cowan seemed like a friendly guy who provided good peer-to-peer influencing tips. As someone at a high-growth SaaS company, I didn't feel that all of this was super relevant - I think it's just quite different managing a physical product vs. software.

There were a few useful topics (HOOKS framework, Customer Discovery ideas), but a vast majority of the information is vague. The best use I got out of this course is googling the important topics and reading articles about them.

Good information, but it felt a bit unstructured with topics jumping from one to the next a bit back and forth. Also, tests were not great as many alternatives made no sense to the questions asked, so you could easily ignore at least 50% of the answers to each question.
The quizzes are poorly written and instructor is very biased towards methodologies he created.
No tiene subtitulo en español.
The quizzes were extremely tough and often, questions made no sense

Some content not explained that well. A bit confusing. The quiz questions are really abstract and don't necessarily test our understanding well. Many times there were 2-3 "correct" answers, but they were looking for a particular one without giving enough context. While useful, the business model canvas was not explained in enough detail. I felt like it was glossed over. A proper introduction to this in the beginning of the course would help with context. Otherwise, learnt a lot, and helpful course.

Good content. However not very convenient way of presenting (making marks on the slides, it is hard to read them), difficult to make notes and the slides available without notes are rather useless. The course is marketed as a beginner level, but this is far from true. A student need to have some experience or education in at least business (luckily I have a lot) and some understanding of digital businesses. The course is not very friendly to those whose English is not native. For instance, the tasks in the tests were sometime very trickily formulated. Somehow more academic language of the lectures would be also more appreciated.

So I have got a lot of useful information, but is was hard to keep some nicely structured summary of each lecture - so almost nothing left for later "memory refreshment".
apresenta o básico sobre Product Management. Bom para quem está começando ou quer começar
Very unclear quiz-questions.
I'd appreciate more detailed content and how to use the tools and less interviews

The course is interesting indeed, but lot of reviews here are right in pointing out that there are also some problems that could be addressed. TO be more specific 1) Lot of content and not enough depth, so lot of topics get only surfaced and not fully explained and understood: 2) This idea of the teacher to scribble/write on top of the slides while explaining is not the best, at least for me. The final slides are very hard to read, and the original slides are not enough cause they missed annotations; 3) More practical examples would have been beneficials

The first three weeks are good, a lot of good content, but he (despite trying) has trouble fitting all the methodologies together in one single framework that is actionable. 4th week is an absolute waste of time.Ideally, to improve the course, the author should give a concise overall picture, concatenating ideas, connecting them with a timeline of the PM's role throughout the product's life cycle/challenges.It seems to me that the course lacks an overarching view of the whole process. At the same time, the author goes through all the views, methodologies, and prisms of what it is to be a PM, he does not make those views compatible, which makes the course lack pragmatism, despite being a good introduction.
course is great but mentor need more reality facts form real business life, use famous companies real cases.
Its ok
I would have been appreciate more practical examples. For instance was a good idea to start from the week 1 to the week 4 to show about to manage a product from scratch in all the steps

Great course overall. I felt the last week have a drop in the content and it was light in what I consider important topics were as the first two weeks were very heavy in content. Balancing the content by extending some important topics at the end of the course will help to improve my opinion on the course. Also, the questions on the quizzes are written in a very tricky way, I don't think it is a helpful way to test knowledge by trying to trick the person in how the questions are being asked, a better way will be to directly test the knowledge of that subject by proving comparisons.
All the quizz questions are vague and the "right" answers are debatable.

The first module was great, from there on a lot of the meat of the course is similar to Agile, but just packaged differently. They are a few noisy question in the MCQ too. It would be better value for money at a lower price point
While I like the course, i feel it doesn't go deep into anything. I would have liked it better if we went deeper to sections like analytics, product planning, market analysis etc.
This is a pretty high level overview for anyone curious about product management.

The course was very practical in its approach with a lot of good sessions with industry practitioners. Also, I learnt a lot of industry & function-specific lingo, tools and frameworks that will help with a structures approach to product management. Alex as a faculty comes across as very friendly and humorous. However, I felt he could have made his lectures a little more structured rather than impromptu. All in all, the course serves as a great primer to product management and one needs to apply the concepts learnt in practice to gain fully from the course.

The course exposed me to various frameworks available to help product managers organize themselves in their work and keep focused on the right things. Would have wished if it went deeper and showed how some concepts can be really applied. I did not get time to internalize the tools. I did understand them as I went along the course and did the quizzes.Also, the Professor was MIA on the discussion forums. I found little meaningful discussion going on there. The experience with the Design Thinking course was better.
This is definitely a good course for a newbie, however as I was parallel looking at other content I see that this course may need a refresher and more practice sessions to make it better
Too much subjective information. Little info about tools, models and techniques. Overall ok
good
The Course is amazing but the slides are almost useless without the drawings made on video.
The content and presentation of this course was great.  I wish the assessment questions were better written and that there were opportunities to practice.
N​eed to alow time to fit the videos in, its a fair bit for a single setting but overall a useful and insightfuil course and one I will come back to.
a​ good course for gaining a comprehensive image of all the prodct lifecycle roadmap and steps.

Overall a good introduction to product management! Some of the modules in the last two weeks felt more like space fillers, but all the important information was well communicated. This gives me a lot to think about going forward with my career!
good

Very good course.  Moves fast.  Mostly very high level.  I'm taking a star off because the course material slides didn't match all the videos and the videos move too fast to take notes without the slides.  Please update the materials!
​Great overview of product manager role, methods and frameowrks. Real PM interviews are a great way to hear about real applications.
goood and interisting :)
Good, some techinical word to be included in lecture related to common daily use words.Overall good
Me gustó el curso. Pero es algo superficial
Super useful tools and particularly enjoyed the interviews with PM's and SME's. This course is must for anyone who wants be better at product management.
podría ser un poco más interactivo , sin embargo tiene información muy valiosa
the speaker talks kind slow therefore i watch it at 1.25 speed, but i def learnd so much from this course, really love it and super easy to follow.

The course is overall good, but it has many videos and less number of hands on assignments to practice and implement what we learn in the course, also the teaching style is not structured which leads to problem while taking notes.
T​his course is great. I learned many things. I should take this course long time ago
That was great opportunity to learn about steps of digital product management. Especially thanks to instructor. Best regards
Some of the technical terms might seem pretty new for a person like me from non-tech backgrount but this course is a good kick-starter for anyone fresh to PM career.

A​lex is a great teacher who keeps your attention and shows enthusiasm for the content. The content is befitting for an introductory course, and gets you thinking about the concepts introduced. The various interviews are a great addition, the interviews with experts as well as those with the alumni.T​he quiz questions could be improved by paying a little more attention to the link between the learning objectives, the course and the questions. Also, it would be nice to get new questions if you re-take a quiz, to really test your understanding. If the quizzes were as good as the course, I would give the course 5 stars.
It was good, learned a lot

​I like all the concepts introduced in this course, and personally, I learned a lot about Product Managment.M​y fav part of this course, is the guest speaker session, which allows learners to listen to many wonderful perspectives of real-life PM and what they do at work. Thanks!
learn alot about Product management

Very good  course for  having and  idea on  how  is to  develope  digital  products  and  the importance of customer focus on it.  It  gives  some  idea  on how  is to lead interdisciplinaries teams  when you  have  the  responsabilities of a product manageres in different  socopes of  a business, that can  be  since engenieers  and  software developement  to business  and growth scope perspective.
Overall great but there are some videos that dont cover some of the questions in the quizzes.

The course broadly covered a great deal of topics that I will explore in more detail on my own. I would not have had exposure to all of these interesting topics without it. I recommend the course and learned a great deal.It is difficult to keep a view of the larger picture as each of the tools and techniques are discussed throughout the course. I lost sight of how everything I learned fits together and is part of a larger, overall process.
Good introduction to Agile methodologies, I think with something practical issues the course could be better

An excellent overview and introduction for new product managers, providing key fundamentals and required shifts in thinking needed to succeed. However, some concepts were confusing, and not enough explanation was provided to understand the distinction. Overall, an excellent course for those starting or pivoting into Product
I enjoyed the course, great vids and enriched by the speakers
Great

Learned a lot from this course on multiple fronts. Liked its extensive coverage of areas, concepts and real-world scenarios that a PM is likely to deal with. My favourite aspect of the course: Currently active PMs sharing insights and best practices gleaned from their work. What I'd like to see more of: A brief lesson backed up by some collateral on how learners can further their learning into one or more of the individual areas (Agile, Design Thinking, Hook Framework, A/B Testing etc).

It's a very good course in general. The instructor delivered clear messages. However, as someone who knew nothing about PM (I'm taking this course for a career change), I found it overwhelmed with bunch of terms (which I think aren't necessary). So instead I tried to grasp the core idea about a successful PM mindset.

While I found the courses in week 1 and week 2 very interesting to help me understand the fundamentals of Product Management, Week 3 and 4 did not match up to the base set up by the first 2 weeks and my interest started to wane. Hope there could be more substantial topics to cover, to make this course more holistic.

Course is very complete, with lots of information.Speaker seems to know a lot; however, it is sometimes difficult to follow up, due to the amount of information and how fast he speaks.  I would recommend giving more real examples.

It's very practical, even you have been working as PM in many years, because you will gain profound suggestion and be stimulated by many ideas of coacher and experts take part in interviewing. I am very appreciated tools and tips of experts who participated in sharing sessions.
A tradução para o português é muito ruim. Eu acabo perdendo bastante informação. Mas o curso é bom.
it was great learning got to know many new things!!
Was a bit too fast for me. Abstract topics require more examples.
Course Content is very good, but it will be more great, if speed of explanation little slower and content can be little more in simple English
Great way to learn. Very interactive
Excelent!
G​reat to have a quick but still good overview of what is like to be a PM and best practices

I learned many terms which i haven't about PM before and the interaction with other company PMs is very impressive. Would like to to recommend to all the beginners who want to get into the forum of Product Management
It was a really nice crash course for Product Management
El curso es un poco plano y si contiene buena información, pero la manera de cómo explica el profesor no se siente que llegue completamente.

Excellent course for getting better insights into product management. The course covers all the aspects of product management ranging from developing a new business to scaling an exisiting business. Also covers a range of methodologies required for a successful product management. The inclusion of product management insights from various industry experts proves to be really handy. Overall the course offers much more than you would expect.
Trustworthy course and up to expectations, it's just the quizzes like puzzles.
INFORMATIVE

A one stop course for getting introduced to modern practices related to product management. Content delivery is good - crisp and clearGuest lectures are good - given by industry professionalsTests are short and comprehensiveRecommended for any one taking up their first product management role

the course is really good and a definite watch before launching a product. I wish there were more real case studies both as part of course and to be submitted as assignments so we could learn how to do the work and get feedback on it

I really enjoyed the application of modern ideas and Mr. Cowan's passion and practical advise. Already being used to the spectacular style of YouTube content creators, I sometimes had to add some dopamine stimulating side content to watch the next video or do the next quiz. If the course creators wish to help younger generations to keep focused on the course's contents, maybe some of these techniques could be added as well. Thanks a lot for the course and for connecting the dots between the start-up world and enterprise software engineering!

The course was very beneficial with so many new concepts to learn. The quality of lectures and materials were high and I truly enjoyed it.I learnt so much and I guess the only issue for me was that sometimes subjects where taught fast and I couldn’t catch up with them.

Thank you for the useful information on this course, I think this is the first step towards the Product Management that people need to study before they practice it,Some exam questions are tricky and requires a lot of study

The course touches a lot of topics. There is a rich content. It did not satisfy my expectations, I was expecting a real life digital product management course not too much theory. I was not comfortable with the design of the course flow, organization of the content and lack of real life examples. The interviews were great, but I was expecting more real life software product management case studies. Most of the examples are outside software and technology.  Presenting of the examples were also not in line with my learning pace. Each process step was not explained with a unique example, there was a lot of jump from one example to another, sometimes very different products, which almost made it impossible to understand the product management process - and align it with the case. The topics are not well aligned with product management process flow. Sometimes, I was lost between videos about what is the agenda and current topic. Good presentation, congratulation about the quality of the videos, slides, and the resources/templates provided.
Grande el instructor y los contenidos. Mejorable la traducción al español.
Great course, and  info proved to be very valuable in enhancing my knowledge in Digital Product Mgmt. A great addition to my background in Project Management.

I really enjoyed this course. I thought it was very well constructed with topics building on previous modules and reinforcing concepts introduced.  The quizzes are you go along are great for checking ones understanding, however found some of the language used in the quesitons difficult to comprehend.   I am a native English speaker but i wonder if others who are not might struggle  - especially around use of double negatives or some what i would call 'colloquial' American.
very nice and interesting course to learn the fundamentals of the product management. Alex is very precise and incisive.
Good overview, not very technical. This is an introduction to some of the main concepts that go into managing products. There's very little hands-on "how to" information but more top down theory.

Very informative and descriptive combined with a very practical course structure. One enjoys the course while learning. Also, the reviews of the industry professional make the course even more authentic. Its very fast paced, but there is only so much you can learn about this vast topic in such little time.
This course teaches basic concepts of product management, cross-functional collaboration, and business success.

The course gives some good examples, and descriptive. However, if the instructor can remove some of the storytelling or examples, and be a little more direct in what he is teaching, then that would make the course easier to follow and to review for points that was unclear or forgotten during the quizzes.
Fantastic course for product managers. Lot of experiences shared by different PM
I had a wonderful experience and learnt many useful new things,

Would have been great if there would be more examples based on ecommerce, digital retail, or development of mobile app stores. It's such a massive market with so many employees and consumers that the examples may be easier to relate to and understand then chickens and feeds :) But overall loved the course
Enjoyed the quality of content and the interviews. On the other hand, the course covers a lot of ground and many of those topics are covered at a very superficial level.

I took this course to start developing my own project. For me it was definitely an eye opener, especially in fundamental questions like personas and problem scenarios, which I think is very important. Based on this course I am going to review my first plan for the project and product development to include some of the concepts from the course. I did not give it five stars, because of the lack of explanations for some of the concepts, for example, what's the difference between the Venture Design process and Five Steps to Epiphany? When and why we should use the one over another? Another reasons is the explanations from Alex are really highlevel sometimes, while you would definitely like to explore some of the concepts in more details.
The course was pretty amazing but alot of things were totally new in the assignments. As a beginner, I had to google alot. which I think is a great thing, it helped me learn more.
Indeed a great course to hear about the whole method of handling new digital goods. I genuinely loved every bit of it and learned a lot of new material. The facilitator was really awesome.
Good set of tools and techniques, some good ideas.
That was very fruitful to understand the digital product management methods and tools
I'm so happy to receive this certificate in Digital Product Management Modern Fundamentals and with the skill acquire, it will enable me to improve my working ability at my jobsite. Thanks a lot
Alex Cowan has extensive knowledge in this subject. However, He tends to speak quickly and without any sufficient pause. I wish Alex Cowan may able to improve His speaking skill.
Some aging concepts - but still a good core course to outline the fundamentals of Product Management.

Great to have a practical overview of the role, responsibilities and technics that a PM can use. The interviews were all concise and very insightful. I would suggest including some exercises that stimulate students to read and analyse the resources section. It is good reading that complements the learning.I'm very happy about the time invested in this course!
A good intro to product management
Good Course
Good intro! I would suggest keeping one of the examples and applying all of the techniques as they were covered, which happened but not in all cases.
it was a wonderful experience! The course materials were highly informative and relatable.
It was great and wonderful. Learnt lot of stuff!

this was indeed one of the most fabulous comprehensive course I have come across; for me personally the segments where business models came in was where I gained good perspective on an org's functioning and strategy
A clear understanding of Product Management, and Leadership tools.
very insightful and practical
A very good introduction to key concepts and techniques for product managers and related roles. Week 4 was not so interesting and engaging as the other weeks.
Great course for introduction to modern Product Management. Helped a lot to gain insights into the mindset required to be a Product Manager.

Excellent course to get a holistic approach of Product Management. The Teacher is great and i found interviews with PMs very insightful.Anyway, I have the feeling that some concepts needed deeper explanation (business model types...)

Very good explanation of the fundamentals. Don't know if I missed this, but much of the contents of this course can be summarized in visuals such as charts, that would've been an awesome resource to have since there are so many tools, techniques and frameworks.
Practical Course. Lots of Guest from relative field delivered useful ideas. All in all a good course
a lot of blurry information: not clear sometimes how really to use this or that
Es un buen curso para aquellos con alguna experiencia previa en disciplinas relacionadas al diseño y de desarrollo de software.
it was nice to have such a remarkable tutor /teachers ,i had alot to learn through this course hope you people arrange more such courses in future

The Course is explained by Mr.Alex , i really like his teachings , very practical with good examples , that makes learning easier .. i wish they'd option for notes to copy and paste in your own word document , and not the website's notes.. and the speed of mr.alex while speaking is lil faster so i suggest do the speed 0.75x in video options .. otherwise a must do course , amazing models to help you design your product for your start up or for your existing product .Thank You Coursera . Thank you Mr Alex . Thank You Virginia University .

Great course! Room for improvement are the pdf slides. They do not always reflect what the professor noted down as well all steps of the animation are on separate slides. It almost triplicates the number of slides.
That's a very nice course. Nowadays which is very useful and helpful methods.
Each product aspect ,process and business model canvas needs to be explained in detail,keeping in mind that a absolute beginner(NON TECH) is learning  the digital concepts completely fresh.
Good course!
Great experience Thanks for alex

It's a great course for someone who is starting this position as myself, at some point I think week 2 it was not getting 100% of my attention but I think it was because there's a lot of short videos about many different topics that needs more explanation, he was changing topics to fast. It was good when he could give examples of what he was saying. I love the interviews and the point of views of the PM's and people he interviewed, Eric one was great. Thanks for the course, I look forward to start practicing most if the things I learned!

A very good course with alot of ground covered. I would suggest users to get a some basic insights on Agile concepts and be clear that alot of what is talked about in this course pertains to product management in the software space. However it surely does give a comprehensive view on the discipline and is a good start for anyone looking to branch out into Product Management
Except for the multiple questions tests, I think is a good introductory course

It's a very wonderful course and I enjoyed every bit of it. In the future I would prefer a less traditional mode of teaching; less of lecture style and more practical ways. The interviews were a good touch though.
Nice course

I had an amazing time going through the notes and grasping new knowledge. Anyways there were typographical errors on the notes/scripts (possibly during transcribing. I can also help transcribe notes and discover errors). Thank you for an amazing experience!!

It is an indeed rich course to take. Challenging and having a deep view of the topic. I suppose the presentations could help more, adding more clarity of the content and also the quiz parts could be less subjective. I strongly recommend taking this course if you need to challenge what you have known so far.
na

The course is very complete, but many contents are designed for someone with previous knowledge in: development, scrum, marketing, business, etc. The teacher explains himself very well but there were parts where I got lost (BMC, seeding features, etc). I recommend this course for anyone interested in learning more about the world of product management
It gives a lot of knowledge, can get a little mixed up, but overall great course!
Covers basic concepts for IT product management , Talked about how to figure out "New product Development" as well as "How to amplify existing product".
Course was great! Alex touched most of the PM fundamentals at a high level. Some sections felt rushed. Alex could have gone little more into details.

The course is very modular and brushes upon exactly what the title says: Fundamentals. It's perfect for newbies who are entering into the Product Management fields and also for existing product managers who are looking for upping their skills and knowledge with the latest trends.
Great course from a knowledgeable instructor. Especially loved sessions with real product managers from out there in the world.
Loved the course material and expertise of the presenter. Thanks for organising this course

Hi,I really like this course learning fundamentals of product management and interviews with industry experts in product management and their views are quite resourceful and insightful for aspiring PMs. Thanks everyone for making this journey very useful. Wish you all happy learning..Ravi
I like the content and I believe I can use it in my daily work.
I felt the course topics were taught in fast paced with not enough time to capture and understand the slides.
Content of the course was quite useful. The only feedback I have is to make the lecture videos slightly less monotonous (maybe by using animations or moving around/ changing locations).
Good, i really learn something new.
Last week content was a little vague which made it difficult to understand
Got to learn a lot of new things. This course gave me a first hand experience of what to expect out of various kind of PM roles. Would definitely recommend.
Some more examples outside software products would have made it more interesting.  Explaining only with software products has its own limitations.

Its' great and flows quickly. It's kind of basic but ALex gives a lot (A LOT!!!) of resources for you to explore beyond the course. There's not much of a "practical" part of the course it's mostly theory so you have to go out and tryit for yourself or commit to the external resources to keep lerning.

It was a nice overview and refresher for the PM role. It is relatively high-level, but hey, it's a 101 course. I wish the roadmap part was a bit more practical, with examples and such. Executives often ask for roadmaps, and there are ways to create good ones without having specific dates and features, which I think is the wrong way to build roadmaps.

Great introductory course from Alex Cowan! I am a junior PM and I found very useful some of the concepts that I learned here. One of the most valuable insights were from the interviews from other PM's. I wish they had more in depth and extensive interviews.
Clear good pacing and information
One of the best courses on Digital Product management with great content for readers and easy to understand and implement. Thank You Coursera

The course is quite good for someone who is a beginner. The guest lectures in between coming from top-notch product managers make it even more interesting as it brings out perspective directly from the industry.
